JOHANNESBURG - The Railway Safety Regulator (RSR) is allowing Prasa to use manual authorisation for train operators. It is used when railway traffic lights are not working. The regulator banned manual authorisation after one train rear-ended another in Germiston, leaving over 200 people injured. READ: Prasa banned from manually authorising trains The regulator’s acting CEO Herman Bruwer said the lift is subject to certain conditions. It says it's satisfied with Prasa’s commitment to addressing safety concerns. "Prasa submitted a corrective action plan to the RSR detailing how they intend to address issues pertaining to manual authorisations of trains during degraded train operations. "The RSR has considered the corrective action plan and is satisfied that Prasa has adequately demonstrated their commitment to address safety concerns raised by the regulator." eNCA